< review>

< Review>
Today in Orange County there are few people who can be described as a "master craftsman". Based on my personal experience I highly recommend Al at Irvine Watch Repair in Tustin as a meticulous master watch repairman who repaired two valuable early 1900s pocket watches owned by my grandfathers. After being told by a high end jewelry/watch store in Newport Beach and a leading independent watch repairman that they could not repair the watches I fortunately found Irvine Watch Repair in Tustin. In addition to the typical watch repair workbench and tools the shop has precision grinding, drilling and polishing equipment for major time piece repair work. This is the place to take a family heirloom or an expensive watch for repair. If you want your treasured broken clock or watch to work again go to Al Afdasta.</Review>

< Text>
Over the weekend, I accidentally dropped my Fiance's Engagement Ring and we needed to get it fixed ASAP. Seeing the great reviews for Time Palace Jewelers, we decided to go there to see if they could help repair the ring.

After arriving at Time Palace Jewelers and speaking with Al and his son, Richard, we found out that the prongs on the ring were bent and the diamond needed to be re-set. For a proper re-setting of the ring, it would take about 3-4 days.

As it was my Fiance's engagement ring, we were concerned about leaving the ring with a store for 3-4 days.

After just picking up the ring today, these concerns were completely unfounded.
Al and his son, like so many other yelp reviews have written, are incredible people. They are patient, honest and trustworthy. They simply know that this is how businesses are supposed to be run.

Especially with an engagement ring, it is incredibly important to find the right people who know what they are doing and Al and his son definitely fit that category. Al made sure both my Fiance and I took a good look at the ring under his microscope, made sure to properly map the diamond (so we know it's ours) and taught us how to recognize our own diamond so no one can try to lie to us.

My diamond was also GIA Certified so he made sure that the number was clearly written down and verified by us personally. Al also made sure we matched up the number when we picked it up to ensure we had our ring.

If you happened to drop your ring like we did, Time Palace Jewelers is the right place to go. There's a reason he has so many great reviews.< /Text>

<user_id>113041921672017450339<//user_id>< review>
My ring finger apparently shrunk between when we sized it and when my now-fiance bought the ring. We came in close to closing (because that was the only time we could go) and we didn't feel rushed at all with the process. I was kind of at a 1/4 size when using the ring sizing tool, but he explained that because there is open space from the bridge on the underside of my ring that it would feel slightly looser than the sizing ring.

My ring is silver and they explained that it would be less expensive to do a gold solder, but that there would be a tiny gold spot at the base of the band. If we used silver solder, there was a risk that the garnet gem would crack from the increased heat, so he would have to remove and reset the gem to avoid that. With the extra cost to remove/reset the gem after soldering it, it was $75. Slightly higher than we expected based on the reviews, but it was less than what my sister paid for hers at South Coast Plaza, and she didn't even need the gem reset because her ring was gold.

The ring was ready in 3 business days - 2 days earlier than I needed it - and the ring was even shinier than when my fiance proposed.

When I got the ring back, it did fit better than the sizer ring because of the open space.
My only complaint is that there was a teeny tiny pockmark where the solder is. I don't wear the ring that often because I work with dogs (I mostly wear it on a velvet cord around my neck), and I actually prefer my silver tarnished (blaspemous, I know) so it won't show and it wasn't a huge deal for me. However, I could see how that could be a big deal for someone else (although I have no idea how common that is for that to happen). So I guess I would deduct 1/2 star for that.

Overall I would definitely recommend them.</review>

<review>When I was younger, I took my engagement ring and wedding band to a local jeweler to get polished.  When they told me that my setting needed to be reinforced or I'd lose my diamond, I was scared enough to go ahead and have them do it without getting a second opinion/quote.  They did the work for $50, and boy did I ever get what I paid for; it was uneven, and actually had a noticeable bubble in it.  The ring looked bad, the tension setting wasn't sleek and flush to my diamond like it used to be... but I was young and didn't want to fight, nor did I have a ton of money to find someone skilled enough to fix it properly.

Fast forward eleven years and a lot of damage to the ring.  There were big nicks and cracks in my ring and I wanted it to get remade so that it looked as beautiful as it was when my husband proposed. I spent a lot of time reading reviews before deciding to head over to Time Palace. What made me decide to trust Internet-Al were his thoughtful, firm responses to negative reviews.  He reminded me of my father, an experienced, honest craftsman who is never afraid to tell someone, "I won't do it for less than $X because if I tried, the work would be bad, and my reputation means a lot to me. I won't do shoddy work to meet your price point."

So I dropped the ring off two days ago along with  a picture of what I hoped Al could do to it.  He gave me a price of between $200-400, depending on labor hours.  I told my husband it would be closer to $400 since I believe in underpromising and overdelivering.

I picked up my ring today and I am thrilled: it is stunning again: sleek, modern, and flawless. To top it all off, Al only charged $200, the very bottom end of what I expected to pay.

If you have a piece that means a lot to you, and you want someone to take good care of it, someone who stakes his reputation on doing his best work every time, head over to Time Palace and entrust it to Al.  You won't be disappointed.</review><pictures>None<//pictures>< response>
None< /response>

< Time>
1410215046080</Time>
< rating>
5</rating>
< review>
I want to take this opportunity to thank Al (Owner of Time Palace Jewelers) for servicing my watches for a past couple of years. I am a watch enthusiast and collector and I have owned several mechanical self-winding automatic watches. One of the thing that intrigues me most about the mechanical watches is its accuracy. Most modern mechanical non-COSC certified watches usually have a typical accuracy of +/- 5 seconds  to +/- 10 seconds per day. That is 99.994% and 99.988% accuracy  respectively.
The watches that I have owned usually have between +6 to +8 seconds per day which is already within COSC certification. However, I am still not very satisfied with the accuracy of my watches. So I brought my watches in for Al to perform a process called "regulation". Basically this is a process of regulating the beat rate by turning the screw and with the time-measuring machine, a qualified watchmaker can accomplish this in a matter of minutes.
This is where Al came in. He has executed this process to perfection. He is very knowledgeable and understands all of mechanical movements. Al has regulated my watches to only +/- 2 seconds per week!! That is when I wear my watch on the day and put it down at night.

So for all watch enthusiasts  out there, I would highly recommend to go to Time Palace Jewelers and have Al adjust/regulate if you found your watches to be too fast or too slow.< /review>

<Pics>None</Pics><Resp>None</Resp><gmapID>0x80dcdbdbf4860481:0xe3c1812f9d3c253</gmapID></record></dataset><record>
<pics>None< /pics>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
<date>1521425805155< /date><gmap_id>0x80dcdbdbf4860481:0xe3c1812f9d3c253</gmap_id><user_name>Joseph Le</user_name><Response>{'time': 1521431378460, 'text': 'Thanks for the awesome review,Joseph! We work hard to meet expectations like yours, and we‚Äôre happy to hear we hit the mark for you. Come back and see us soon. Al!'}< /Response><text>I don't post reviews very often (2nd one on Google), but  I really had to jump in here and write a review for Al.

First, a little bit about Al (the proprietor of Time Palace/1st Watch) that I found out by gleaning the internet. Al is a 3rd generation watch maker. He has a son who also works with him in the shop, so that makes 4 generations of watch making in his family. He also has a BS in Electrical Engineering and an MBA. If nothing, at least his career paths indicate a meticulous and dedicated nature.

The reason I know all this about him was because I needed to bring in my Rolex for a new crystal, and picking a watch maker to work on your Rolex isn't a casual matter. Finding a watch maker who is familiar with Rolexes is not particularly difficult--even though Rolex makes its own watch movements, the theory behind mechanical watch movements is generally the same across all manufacturers, and Rolex movements (because they make their own) are well discussed and documented. However, because Rolex makes its own watch movements, replacement movements can cost thousands of dollars if your watch maker biffs the innards of your watch. Therefore, finding a good watch maker who is meticulous and stands behind his work is more important than ensuring that your watch goes back to the factory repair center.

Onward. Al gave me a straight forward quote to replace my crystal. The price was good to fair. Al also discussed overhauling my watch with me. He indicated that it wasn't necessary (as my watch had just been overhauled last year), but that it was recommended to ensure that the watch continues to function properly.  He left the decision entirely up to me, and his quote for the overhaul was very good. I half expect a watch maker to insist on an overhaul whenever they work on a watch for liability reasons (close up a watch that hasn't had its gasket changed and the watch starts leaking, then suddenly it's the last watch maker's fault). So, I was pleasantly surprised that he didn't insist on an overhaul. I got an overhaul done anyway, but that's beside the point.

Al indicated that he would have to order the crystal for my watch. That's fair--at least he does the work himself in-house and doesn't send it off to another watch maker as is the case with many/most jewelry stores who say they work on Rolexes. So, he quoted me "a few days, but no more than a week." If I wanted it sooner, he could arrange for overnight shipping of the new crystal. No thanks, I said--take your time and I'll pick it up "whenever."

"Whenever" turned out to be the next day before noon. Whiskey. Tango. Foxtrot. That was fast! I dropped the watch off at 3:30 the day before, and he had a new crystal in his shop, replaced it, and overhauled my watch (which includes taking it apart, cleaning the parts individually, replacing all the gaskets, polishing/buffing fine scratches out of the case and band, and putting it all together), and called me before noon the next day.

Bonus: He also puttied off a smudge from the movement of another watch I was wearing when I came in to pick up my Rolex. The fingerprint could be seen through the caseback viewing window and must have been there from when it was assembled. Gratis. On the spot. Couldn't have hoped for more.

In sum: 1) Fast. Really fast. 2) Highly professional, educated, and clear communicating proprietor. 3) Work done on-site in a very clean and well organized work shop. 4) Skilled enough to not be afraid of people watching over his shoulder while he fiddles with microscopic watch parts under a microscope.< /text>< user_id>

< text>
Truly incredible service.

What an absolute joy it was to find this place and have a few of my watches serviced.

I had batteries replaced on two and a loose dial marker reset on a different watch. The battery replacement and the marker fix were very reasonably priced I thought, but after considering it a little more I feel as if they were an absolute bargain. For this level of service I would've paid more. I wanted to tip or something but instead I will just never go anywhere else.

Talking with the VERY VERY experienced store owner made the entire experience for me. Mr. Afdasta mentioned he was a 3rd generation master watch and clockmaker. He thoroughly proved he is a master. He let me observe the disassembly and internals of my watches and explained to me what he was doing in each step.

He puts his workbench in the front of the store. Not behind a counter. Not in the back. He does such masterful work, there's no reason not to. What a great idea!

When other customers entered he gave them very accurate and transparent estimates on price and when the work would be completed. It seems so simple but it is baffling that other businesses just can't do this right. Mr. Afdasta handles it with ease.

<UserId.>105919149214553372344< /UserId.><username>Josephine Huang< /username>< date>
1553545758453<//date>
< Rating>
4</Rating>
< Review>
Went at 12:30pm on a Monday. Parking was plentiful, but it is inside of a shopping plaza so there's plenty of space. The store itself is a little hidden in the corner of the plaza, near Starbucks. Inside it was really spacious, with cute decor and furniture. I really like the aesthetic of the store. The employee I interacted with was a male, and he seemed knowledgeable about the teas. I didn't ask very many questions as I was in a bit of a rush. I chose the Grapefruit Punch drink, and was surprised to find pieces of actual grapefruit inside. It's a mix of grapefruit juice and oolong tea. It didn't take very long for my drink to come out, but the store itself was not very crowded, probably only 3-4 other customers waiting. The drink was very refreshing, but if you don't like grapefruit I wouldn't recommend it. The best part of the drink was that it wasn't overly sweet, and tasted very natural and of high quality. Next time I'm going to try the Rose Garden drink, it seemed to be very popular here! The menu is a decent size, with lots of refreshing drinks that aren't normally on tea menus. Overall, the experience I had was enjoyable, and I would definitely bring some friends back here!</Review>

<username>Alizen</username><Date>1549763426497<//Date>< Rating>
3<//Rating>
< Text>
Despite it being the grand opening, Red Straw wasn‚Äôt really as busy as I anticipated.

The location is found in Cypress Village shopping center right next to Pho Vinai and the recently opened Cauldron. Upon viewing the menu, I have to say that these are relatively expensive drinks compared to what‚Äôs around the area but I wanted to try something new so I decided to give them a shot.

THAI TEA SALTED CREAM ($4.50) ‚Äî first off, the fact that the beverage was given to me with the cream already coming apart was beyond disappointing. Part of what makes a boba shop so successful is it‚Äôs ability to not only provide excellent taste but also excellent aesthetic. This drink was not that at all.... One thing to note is that because the salted cream goes on top of the drink, you cannot adjust the sweetness level as it will literally just be Thai tea.

COFFEE SEA SALT CREAM ($5.75) ‚Äî just like the Thai tea, the cream was coming apart and mixing itself within the drink. This led to a very sad photo that made me question if they had received proper training prior to the grand opening.

SERVICE
The cashier was sweet but otherwise I was disappointed at this aspect as well. I had to ask if I could spin the wheel on their grand opening and I had fortunately gotten 50% off which made this visit worth it. Other than that, the two cashiers were talking to each other and decided to finish their conversation before helping me...

SPEED
Because it wasn‚Äôt particularly busy, the speed was average. I got my drinks around the estimated wait time.

Overall, I would not make a special trip to come out here for a second visit due to price, value, and service. One thing I did like, however, is the fact that they have isothermic bags to go!</Text>

<Review>New tea/boba place in town but really expensive with long wait time.

It is pretty easy to locate, Google Map took me right to the location. It's located in the Cypress Village shopping complex, exactly where Juice It Up used to be [next to Starbucks]. It has private parking lot, so there is ample amount of parking space. Redstraw provides indoor as well as outdoor seating options. Really minimal and modern style decor.

I ordered Thai Sea Salt Cream tea and Coffee Sea Salt Cream [both iced and both with boba]. It took them 35 minutes to make since they brewed it in front of me and I could see all the ingredients being used. I appreciated it when they asked for the percent of sweetness I would want in my coffee: 25%, 50%, 75% or 100%. Redstraw only provides one size for all the items on their menu. Personally, compared to the quantity one gets I believer it's overpriced.< /Review><response>None<//response>< gmapID>

<text>Great place to walk around and enjoy some of the beautiful architecture inspired by Nordic culture. Grass roof, powerful carvings, heavy wood doors with iron hardware, and stained glass windows inspire the pride in my heritage. Europeans brought great beauty to this realm. The lake is clean n clear, the island is pretty too, and it‚Äôs an area away from the more boisterous gatherings of people in Tahoe because of the walk it takes to get there and back. Beautiful home and beautiful spot. It's a steep hike on a very easy to walk on path. Small legs will probably need assistance. But it was worth the trek to see the beautiful sites and this beautiful home. There are picnic tables to have lunch and kayak rentals. The falls is breathtaking and would be a great day trip!< /Review>

0x809986f8cb869efd:0xd79554c750511182</gmap_id>
<review>Fascinating tour of a beautiful 1920s mansion built at the short of picturesque Emerald Bay in Lake Tahoe. Full of Scandinavian workmanship, building methods, design features, and art motifs, it is really a fascinating architectural marvel. The tour is informative. A one-mile hike is required to reach the home on foot--no car access. It is downhill down and all uphill back to the parking lot. Boat access is conceivable. Well worth a visit.< /review>< pictures>

5<//rating>
< review>
Very cool Castle on the bank of Emerald Bay. We've always hiked there as it's gorgeous there.

They have a small visitor center where you can get food/drinks (snacks really) and bathrooms.

There's a nice beach as well.</review>

<Review>Beautiful hike, but keep in mind it is going back be a little taxing for those not in shape or if the weather is warm
Definitely should take some water with you.  If you forgot  the store at the bottom sell water and Gatorade (not always cold on hot days, sine since everyone is buy them when it is warm out). I have been told there is a longer trail back up, but we have yet to try it.

Tour is $15 which all goes back into keeping Vikingsholm maintained.

The beach in the summertime can get crowded early.
You can also rent kayaks and SUP by the hour with discounts for multiple hours. You can kayak over the island to see the Tea House.< /Review>< userid>

It was a bit of a disappointment for us. < Text>
Emerald Bay area is just awesome. Water is quite cold but if you enjoy swimming and even snorkeling, I highly recommend the beach by Vikingsholm, the water is super clear and clean and there's a lot of cool stuff to see for snorkeling. It's a mile hike down to get there and a mile hike back up, kinda rough, but it's not too bad, a moderate level of steepness.</Text>

<Rating>4< /Rating><Text>Absolutely stunning home.  Emerald Bay is beautiful.  Breath taking.  Be aware if you want to visit this historical home...it cost $10 to park and is very hard to find parking there.  We had to park on the side of the highway about a half mile away.  Once you get to the trail head its about a mile down hill to the house and beach.  You know what that means, right?  It's a mile UP hill back.  With tired cranky children it can challenging.  Bring a stroller if you can.< /Text>< Pics>

<UserId.>101852149063981724666< /UserId.>< username>
Josh Farnsworth<//username>
< date>
1564016344562</date>
<rate>3</rate>< review>
Pack water!!! No way in or out without a boat or hiking. There is a paved road but only state park employees and volunteers can drive it. The hike is 1.6 miles on the paved road (steep walk back) . The Rubicon trail from the state park is 1.7 miles on a Rocky, muddy, dirt trail with ups and downs. Its a nice hike if you are prepared for it. (We had sandals on so it wasn't very pleasant.) I think the state should allow a shuttle service to use the paved road. It would be a good way to earn money for the state parks. There is a very limited selection of cold drinks at the tiny shop (provided they keep it stocked up and cold- they use a mini fridge)< /review>

< user_name>
Natalie Ruvalcaba<//user_name>
<Time>1564700066936<//Time><rating>3</rating>< review>
Tickets were $15 per person for the "Mansion" and quite frankly it's really small. Not at all what we had imagined. Also, just so you know...you must hike down to get to this location from the top of Emerald Bay. There are some free parking spaces off the road but are very limited. Main parking is $10 for the day. The hike is pretty steep coming up. Do not recommend taking strollers. Road is rocking and space at beach is very limited. Perfect place for kayaking and paddleboarding.</review>

<Text>Vikingsholm is a great place to visit, offering beautiful architecture and a fascinating story behind its creation (no Viking colony on Lake Tahoe, sorry).

It seems like most people drive here but we arrived from the water, beaching the boat right in front of Vikingsholm during a day of exploring Emerald Bay and Fannette Island.

Make sure to bring your camera as you'll definitely want to take pictures of this place!< /Text><user_id>109292797534330207421</user_id><user_name>Ruger Carstens</user_name></record></dataset><record>

<user>105306901194213777094< /user>< Rating>
5</Rating>
<Text>Really nice hike down to the water, and the house is beautiful. The park service warns that the path is very steep, and while this is true it is much easier going down than it is coming back up, so be prepared for that. The hike back up to the parking lot is much harder because of the consistent grade, bring water and wear comfortable shoes. The house is only open for tours between memorial day and September 30th, but even if you can't go inside it's still worth a trip. The exterior architecture is very intricate, and there's no other buildings quite like this anywhere in the US that I know of.</Text>< gmap_id>

<user>107498835119847685443</user>< username>
Erik Pace< /username>
<time>1568788734267< /time><Rate>5< /Rate>< Review>
Okay, this place will appeal to many people. Exercise enthusiasts (that mile climb back up is NO JOKE), but especially history buffs and fans of Scandinavian (Viking) design and artifacts. Not to mention it is on the drop dead gorgeous Emerald Bay beach. The hike up almost gave me a heart-attack, but I'd do again again anytime to see that house and lounge in the area. Next time I'm going in by boat, though...<//Review>

<user_id>108201441499441125941</user_id>< Name>
J Scott< /Name>
<time>1567637033102< /time>< Rate>
5< /Rate>
< Review>
Get there before 10:00 a.m. to make sure you get a parking spot unless you want to park along the road.  It's a mile walk down and a pretty steep walk up but it's all on relatively even surface.   They have a small gift shop at the bottom that has some ice cream and water.  There are also restrooms but no water in the restrooms.

The tour of Vikingsholm was 30 minutes long and a guide provided a brief history of the family and property.  You could look into the rooms but only were able to enter one.  Still, it was worth it to us and we enjoyed Inspiration Point, a hike up to Cascade Falls and a visit to Vikingsholm.</Review>

4<//Rating>
<user_name>Sumit Sen</user_name>< date>
1583193292533<//date>
<UserId.>116747198926175092195<//UserId.>< Review>
A nice 2 mile hike for families with moderate elevation.  The trail goes from a parking lot to the Vikingsholm mansion and beach.  It is partially shaded by tall pine trees and cliffs, and several streams cross under it at different points.  The house is closed in winter but is still worth visiting to see it from outside. It's a very unusual medieval-style Nordic mansion constructed around a courtyard and with a partial sod roof.  The beach is very inviting with some picnic benches and a pier.  The neighboring island can be visited by boat (in summer I presume) but you aren't allowed to swim there.<//Review>

<review>Going back in time to feel the gentle calm in part of Tahoe history. The architecture is intriguing, beautiful, artistic, understated Norwegian Castle with it's modesty as opposed to palatial extravagance. So if you're expecting grandiose, save the trip, if you're looking for a melancholy walk back in time to learn a piece of history and love for the appreciation of natural beauty, it's a must see. The restrooms are provided but be warned, they're the pits! Literally!</review>< pics>

< Review>
Although it was quite a hike to get to (especially on the way back up, 1 mile up hill) the staff were great, friendly and accommodating. It was worth it. Breathtaking views! Easy process and the equipment was reliable and easy to use. Make sure you leave some energy for thr hike back up hill! We (3 kids and i) rented one kayak and a paddle board for a full day. We arrived at 12p and brought it back at 5p. Exhausting but exhilarating!  Nice beach and peir was fun to jump off of! Water was beautiful...just like Hawaii...can see through to the bottom.< /Review>

<name>Mike Johnson</name><Date>1550613747537< /Date>< rating>
5< /rating>
< review>
Beautiful old mansion based on Scandinavian architecture. Awesome layout. Beautiful river is close. It is a fairly long hike to get there (one mile) and the hike back isnt easy. Not rough, just steep. Stop and catch your breath. Plan your day so it isn't closed (inside) when you get there. And (paid) parking is limited so get there early. Hours were 10:30 to 4:30, seasonally for guided tour.  You might want to confirm. Kayak rental nearby. Pack water and snacks. Highly recommended!< /review>

<username>Maricsa Palmas-perez< /username>< Rate>

</record></dataset><record>
< userid>
105842199017447967766< /userid>
< username>
Abz Lee</username>
< Date>
1528779822957<//Date>
< rating>
5</rating>
<text>Beautiful Castle and beach! You have to park  at the top of the hill at an overlook which requires payment. Then, you hike down a steep trail quite a ways to the castle which lies next to the shore. The Castle was closed when I visited, but the outside views are absolutely gorgeous. (There are tours during summer which require payment as well.) You can see the island in the bay from the beach and walk around the castle. The nature and animals in the area were wonderful as well. There were geese on the beach, jays following us around the building and even a few chubby chipmunks hanging out along the path. The park ranger was friendly as well. Overall, the place was beautiful and welcoming. I highly recommend the hike to see it!<//text>< Pictures>
None< /Pictures>

None< /resp>

106614229567752325323< /userid>
< time>
1530508151696</time>
< Review>
Historic building,  if you enjoy California and lake tahoe history it is a nice tour.  There is a 1 mile walk to the lake and building.  Not bad going down. But going back up may be a struggle if you are not ready for it.  Some spots are steep and I saw a few groups really struggling. Carry your own water. It is not available at the bottom.
Parking is a problem.  The small lot ($10 charge) fills up early and you have to park on the highway and walk.  We got there at noon and had a 1/2 mile walk just to get to the trail.< /Review>

<Text>Beautiful mansion. We hiked in from Bliss State Park on the Rubicon Traill, about 4 miles away.   The Emerald State Park parking lot was full.  Get there early and have alternate parking options in mind ahead of time.  The trail was difficult for me (sedintary), but easier for my husband (walks everyday).   The trail was beautiful, it even went down to the water at one point.  Got some ex$pen$ive ice cream treats at the ticket office.  After the hike, the Haagen-Dazs was heavenly and worth every penny.
Emerald Bay was gorgeous especially as seen from the trail.  The water is beautiful, and the tour is a nice rest before heading back.  Give yourself time to enjoy this beautiful area.< /Text>< Pics>

<response>None</response>< Gmap_id>
0x809986f8cb869efd:0xd79554c750511182< /Gmap_id>
< pics>
None</pics>
< Text>
A quaint and very unique home/castle right on the shores of Emerald Bay.  You can get here by boat, kayak, hiking the Rubicon trail, or from the main road above (parking area day permit required) and then hike down on a somewhat steep but short trail.  Vikinsholm is available to see by buying a tour either at the next door visitor center or by purchasing one of the local guided boat tours.  Bring your camera, extra water, snacks, and swimsuits if you want to take a dip in the bay and spend a little time on the very small beaches.  Most people just wear their swimsuits and hike in. There is a restroom, but I don't think there was any running water.</Text>

<Review>Gives you that old haunted house feeling, even though there are 38 rooms they are quite small and crampy with all the furnishing. Best view is the gorgeous emerald bay at the front on the place. Can't imagine what must the owner felt walking out the front door and into the bay each morning. Best to go there by boat otherwise it's a long 2 miles hike to the place especially in a hot summer day! Definitely not for older folks because of the difficult path.</Review>< Rating>

<Rating>4< /Rating>< review>
Great hike! I'd recommend going in the morning between May- Sept when you can take a tour of the mansion. Hike back up later in the day can be difficult if you're not dressed to hike. (aka: don't wear jeans! Lol!)

Also, I'm a lil outta shape...it's good cardio. While you're at the lake you can also take a boat ride or just paddle board, kayak or fish. No bikes or pets allowed so leave them at home for this one. 4/5 ‚≠ê's.<//review>

(Translated by Google) In the same lake Tahoe.
A wonderful place.
Leave your car on the road, to the side to avoid paying $ 10 for parking (very small). From the parking lot there is a road of 1.5 km approx. that goes down to the lake.
Crystal clear waters and large forest Ideal for children despite the walk.
There are signs that indicate the cold of its waters, but it is not so much, not much more than the water of the beaches of the Costa Brava.
I advise you to pass the beach and look for a more intimate corner.
There are picnic tables throughout the forest.
Next to it is a small waterfall.

(Original)
En el mismo lago Tahoe.
Un lugar maravilloso.
